Day 3 case
The following code can be saved as a html file. This code creates a styled to-do list where users add tasks by typing into the input field and pressing Enter. Each task contains safely inserted text and a delete button, while clicking the task toggles its completed appearance. A single event listener on the <ul> uses event delegation to handle both completion and deletion for all current and future tasks.
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
li {
padding: 8px;
margin: 4px 0;
background: #f0f0f0;
border-radius: 4px;
display: flex;
justify-content: space-between;
cursor: pointer;
}
li.done {
text-decoration: line-through;
opacity: 0.5;
}
.delete-btn {
color: red;
border: none;
background: none;
cursor: pointer;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<input type="text" id="taskInput" placeholder="input and press enter" />
<ul id="taskList"></ul> <script>
const input = document.getElementById("taskInput");
const list = document.getElementById("taskList");
input.addEventListener("keydown", (e) => {
if (e.key === "Enter" && input.value.trim() !== "") {
addTask(input.value.trim());
input.value = "";
}
});
function addTask(text) {
const li = document.createElement("li");
const span = document.createElement("span");
span.textContent = text;
const delBtn = document.createElement("button");
delBtn.textContent = "✕";
delBtn.className = "delete-btn";
li.appendChild(span);
li.appendChild(delBtn);
list.appendChild(li);
}
list.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
if (e.target.classList.contains("delete-btn")) {
e.target.closest("li").remove();
} else if (e.target.tagName === "SPAN" || e.target.tagName === "LI") {
e.target.closest("li").classList.toggle("done");
}
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
1/ HTML Structure
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
/* CSS */
</style>
</head>
<body>
<input type="text" id="taskInput" placeholder="input and press enter" />
<ul id="taskList"></ul> <script>
/* JavaScript */
</script>
</body>
</html>
The CSS is embedded directly in the HTML file. Within the <body>, the JavaScript appears after the <input> and <ul>elements, which have an id attribute for each.
2/ CSS elements
<style>
li {
padding: 8px;
margin: 4px 0;
background: #f0f0f0;
border-radius: 4px;
display: flex;
justify-content: space-between;
cursor: pointer;
}
li.done {
text-decoration: line-through;
opacity: 0.5;
}
.delete-btn {
color: red;
border: none;
background: none;
cursor: pointer;
}
</style>First, the li element selector applies the base styles to every <li> element on the page. Next, the combined selector li.done defines an alternative visual state—strikethrough text and reduced opacity—for <li> elements that have the done class; JavaScript can add or remove this class during user interaction. Finally, the .delete-btn class selector applies its ruleset to every element with the delete-btn class, which in this example styles the task deletion buttons.
3/ JS method with DOM
<script>
const input = document.getElementById("taskInput");
const list = document.getElementById("taskList"); // Listener 1 for keydown event
input.addEventListener("keydown", (e) => {
if (e.key === "Enter" && input.value.trim() !== "") {
addTask(input.value.trim());
input.value = "";
}
});
function addTask(text) {
const li = document.createElement("li");
const span = document.createElement("span");
span.textContent = text;
const delBtn = document.createElement("button");
delBtn.textContent = "✕";
delBtn.className = "delete-btn";
li.appendChild(span);
li.appendChild(delBtn);
list.appendChild(li);
}
// Listener 2 for click event
list.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
if (e.target.classList.contains("delete-btn")) {
e.target.closest("li").remove();
} else if (e.target.tagName === "SPAN" || e.target.tagName === "LI") {
e.target.closest("li").classList.toggle("done");
}
});
</script>
First, two references are created for the <input> and <ul> DOM elements by selecting them by their IDs. The first event listener monitors the predefined keydown event; when the user presses Enter and the input contains non-whitespace text, the callback calls addTask(), which creates a new <li> containing the task text and a delete button, adds it to the list, and clears the input field. The second listener uses event delegation to handle click events on the <ul>: clicking a delete button removes its corresponding <li>, while clicking a task’s <span> or <li> toggles the done class and its associated completed-task styling.
4/ What is event delegation and why we like it?
Event delegation means attaching one event listener to a parent element and using it to handle events from its child elements. How it works is closely related to the DOM structure. The click events normally “bubble” upward through the DOM in such order: <button> → <li> → <ul> → <body> → document . If the user clicks a delete button, the click begins on the button and then travels upward to the <ul>, where the listener is waiting for it and handles it.
list.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
// Handle clicks from elements inside the list
});Event delegation is particularly useful for dynamically created elements. The delete buttons do not exist when the page initially loads, but their click events still bubble to the existing <ul> listener.
Without delegation, every new button needs its own listener and we have to create it one by one:
delBtn.addEventListener("click", () => {
li.remove();
});
